        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1958-10-11T01:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1958-10-11T01:30:00-05:00" n="253"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d253">
                <head>253. Telegram From the <gloss type="from">Embassy in Iran</gloss> to the
                        <gloss type="to">Department of State</gloss>
                    <note n="0" type="source" xml:id="d253fn0">Source: Department of State, Central
                        Files, 788,00/10–1158. Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Tehran</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1958-10-11T10:00:00+03:30">October 11, 1958, 10 a.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>740. Following is Embassy comment <gloss target="#t_SNIE1">SNIE</gloss>
                        34–58.<note n="1" xml:id="d253fn1">
                        <ref target="#d249">Document 249</ref>.</note> Emb agrees with <gloss
                        target="#t_SNIE1">SNIE</gloss> except for points listed below which are
                    reflected in Embdesp 176, Sept. 4, 1958:<note n="2" xml:id="d253fn2">In despatch
                        176 the Embassy assessed the current and future political situation in Iran.
                        (Department of State, Central Files, 788.00/9–458)</note>
                </p>
                <list>
                    <label>(a)</label>
                    <item>Unless Iraq used as base anti-Iran activities even at cost Iraqi national
                        interests, unless Shah assassinated, or unless hitherto invisible leadership
                        talent is employed against Shah, Emb believes Shah can remain in power
                        indefinitely though precariously.</item>
                    <label>(b)</label>
                    <item>There is real possibility that general econ advances combined with
                        politico-psychological reforms toward which Shah is hesitantly moving may
                        reorient important elements urban middle class and decrease pressure on
                        regime. This possibility provides grounds cautious optimism that regime may
                        with luck and skill consolidate its position and is not inevitably
                        doomed.</item>
                    <label>(c)</label>
                    <item>With gradual recovery from panic emotions following Baghdad coup, recent
                        mass promotions security forces, accomplished and <pb facs="0630" n="596"
                            xml:id="pg_596"/> upcoming changes in top military command, and
                        continuous rechecking security records top officers, armed forces probably
                        do not represent immediate threat to regime, although officers are far from
                        solidly loyal and could still turn against Shah if skillful leadership were
                        to appear.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_WET1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Wailes</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
